<section xml:id="section-introduction">
  <title>Introduction</title>
  <subsection xml:id="subsection-what-is-calculus">>
    <title>What Is Calculus</title>
    <p>
      In almost all universities, the core and starting point of
      academic mathematics is calculus. Why is this so? What is
      calculus and why is it so important? In this introductory
      section, I want to give you a brief idea of what calculus is
      about, as well as provide some motivation for why it ought to be
      studied. 
    </p>
    <p>
      Calculus is the study of the dynamic behaviour of
      functions. Okay, that's a definition, but why does that help?
      What is a function and why is the study of the behaviour of
      functions so central? Why `dynamic'?
    </p>
    <p>
      An understanding of function is prerequisite to this course
      (though some review will be provided in early sections.) But let
      me state a definition regardless. In brief, a function is a
      mathematical way of encoding the dependance of one quantity on
      another. Mathematics is a descriptive language that seeks to
      capture the quantitative aspects of the world. In the world,
      many quantites depend on other quantities. In an environment,
      humidity may depend on temperature. In a vehicle, fuel efficieny
      may depend on speed.  In an economy, productivity may depend on
      interest rates. A function is the mathematical thing that
      measures these relationships.
    </p>
    <p>
      This is why a function is, arguably, the most important
      mathematical tool for describing the quantitative world. The
      (quantitative) world is not a collection of completely seperated
      and independent measurements; it is a collection of deeply
      interconnected systems. It is full of dependencies. The function
      is the tool that describes the reality of the (quantitative)
      world in all its interdependencies. 
    </p>
    <p>
      In particular, most quantities in the world depend on time and
      change over time. Very little in the world is completely static.
      A function can describe how something changes and evolves over
      time. 
    </p>
    <p>
      In this way, mathematicians use functions to model the world. To
      be able to do so, they need a theory of functions and their
      behaviour. That theory is calculus. 
    </p>
    <p>
      But some of you might now ask: why do we need a new theory? We
      learned about functions in high school and the algebraic
      techniques of high school mathematics were pretty good at
      describing functions. This is true: algebra goes a long way to
      understanding functions. However, algebra has one very important
      and significant weakness: it is static. Algebra can calculate
      one unknown quantity from other known quantities, but it is only 
      a snapshot, a single fixed moment in time. Once quantities start
      changing and shifting, algebra can not longer keep track.
    </p>
    <p>
      This is why we need the new techniques of calculus. Functions
      are dynamic: they are constantly change, constantly in flux.
      They represent systems where nothing is static. The new tools in
      calculus (the derivative, the integral, the infinite series) are
      all ways to understand dynamic systems, where the change is
      happening all around. 
    </p>
    <p>
      To get to the tools of calculus, I'm going to spend several
      sections on material that may be review for some of you. First,
      I'm going to cover anlytic geometry.  This is the set of
      geometric tools mathematicians use to understand the shape of
      functions, as well as other shapes in two dimensional space. It
      is necessary for understanding and, in particular, visualizing
      functions.  Following analytic geometry, I'm going to talk about
      the concept of a function and go over the main properties and
      operations. Ater this preparation, we can move on to the start
      of what is actually considered calculus. 
    </p>
  </subsection>
  <subsection xml:id="subsection-motivating-problems">
    <p>
      To motivate the course, I want to describe a few important
      problems: problems which cannot be solved just with algebra. I
      hope these seem practical and worthwhile to you, so that it
      makes sense why we would need to develop a whole new kind of
      mathematics to solve these problems. 
      To recap from the last section, I want to describe the
      (quantitative) world. I observe that in the world, quantities
      are interrelated and interdependent. These quantities  are also
      dynamic, constant in flux. To make a mathematical description of the
      world, the description must also be dynamic and interdependant.
      That requires functions, and calculus is the study of their
      dynamic behaviour. Here are some such dynamic problems. 
    </p>
    <subsubsection xml:id="subsubsection-motivating-population">
      <title>Motivating Problem: Population Growth</title>
      <p>
        If I observe a population (human, animal, plant, etc.), one of
        most common behaviours to observe is percentage growth. How
        much a population changes over a unit of time usually depend
        on how large the population is, and that dependence is very
        commonly a percentage. In Canada, for example, the population
        growth over the last few decades has usually been between one
        and three percent. This makes sense: a larger population can
        produce more offspring, and under consistent conditions, will
        produce offspring at some consistent rate. That's a
        percentage.
      </p>
      <p>
        As just a percentage, of course, algebra can calculate this.
        If I have a population of 7 million and a percentage growth
        of  <m>1.7\%</m> per year, then I can just calculate that the
        population will increase by <m>119,000</m> individuals. This
        is algebra, but this is only a single calculation. It tells me
        the growth at a moment, but no more.
      </p>
      <p>
        What is I wanted a more holistic picture? What is I wanted a
        <em>function</em> that describes the popluation over time?
        This algebra cannot solve. Percentage growth descripes a
        growth rate of a function. But it doesn't tell you what the
        function actually is. To find the function, you need a
        mathematical method to start with a growth rate and produce
        the original functions. That's the kind of dynamic problem
        that algebra can't solve
      </p>
      <p>
        This is a pretty universal problem: it doesn't just apply to
        population. Anything that is described by a growth rate has
        this problem: how do you get to a function from the growth
        rate. This arise in many places: rates of heating and cooling; 
        rates of financial or economic growth; rates of production of
        a new chemical in a chemical reaction; rates of radio-active
        decay; I could go on. That said, I choose population because
        its importance, and because it is a biological problem.
        Historically (as I will discuss shortly), biology was not the
        motivating science for the invention of the calculus. But
        population dynamics in biology is a perfect environment to
        demonstrate the value of calculus. Throughout this course,
        I'll rely most heavily on population dynamics as motivation: I
        want this to be a course about understanding the nature of
        population growth and how it can be reasonably described
        mathematically. 
      </p>
    </subsubsection>
    <subsubsection xml:id="subsubsection-motivating-velocity">
      <title>Motivating Problem: Velocity</title>
      <figure xml:id="figure-slope-linear">
        <caption>Slope of a Linear Function</caption>
        <image xml:id="figure10" width="60%">
          <asymptote>
            size(10cm);
  
            import graph;
  
            xaxis("$t$");
            yaxis("$p$");
  
            real f(real x) {return x/3;}
  
            draw(graph(f,0,8));
  
            draw((6,2)--(6,1)--(3,1));
  
            label("$\Delta p$",(6,1.5),E);
            label("$\Delta t$",(4.5,1),S);
            label("$a = \frac{\Delta p}{\Delta t}$",(4.5,1.5),NW);
            label("$p=at$", (8,8/3),E);
          </asymptote>
        </image>
      </figure>
      <p>
        My first example was biological. However, the history of
        calculus comes more from physics and geometry. So, let me go
        back to that histor     My first example was biological.
        However, the history of calculus comes more from physics and
        geometry. So, let me go back to that historyy 
        Coming from physics, the velocity problem is one of the basic
        motivating problems of calculus. Assume there is an object
        moving in one dimension. I can describe its position as a
        function <m>p(t)</m> where <m>p</m> is position in terms of
        time <m>t</m>. I want to know its velocity.
      </p>
      <p>
        If <m>p(t) = at + b</m> is a linear function, then algebra can
        answer this question. With this linear function, for each unit
        of time the object travels <m>a</m> units of distance. The value
        <m>a</m> is the velocity. Geometrically, the velocity is
        measured by the slope of the straight line graph of <m>p(t)</m>.
        The slope is calculated by the ratio of the change in <m>p</m>,
        <m>\Delta p</m>, to the change in <m>t</m>, <m>\Delta t</m>.
      </p>
      <p>
        That's fine for liner function: they hav e a constant
        velocity. But with most moving objects, velocity is not
        constant. The graph of such a function is not a straight line. 
      </p>
      <figure xml:id="figure-tangent-line">
        <caption>Non-Constant Velocity</caption>
        <image xml:id="figure11" width="60%">
          <asymptote>
            size(10cm);
  
            import graph;
  
            xaxis("$x$");
            yaxis("$y$");
  
            real f1(real x) {return (x^3-x^2+x+1)/8;}
            real f2(real x) {return 3/8*x - 11/76;}
  
            draw(graph(f1,0,2.2));
            draw(graph(f2,0,3));
          </asymptote>
        </image>
      </figure>
      <p>
        The line drawn in <xref ref="figure-tangent-line"/> is called
        a tangent line. It just touches the graph at one points. It's
        a straight line, so it has a slope, and therefore a velocity.
        Finding this slope would be a way to understand the velocity
        of this object. 
      </p>
      <p>
        But wow do I calculate a tangent line? Algebra has trouble
        with this problem. All I have is a point and the function.
        There is no second point with which to define a line and thus
        a slope. So here is another problem to motivate calculus.
        Geometrically, how can I find the slope of a tangent line. In
        terms of movement, how can I determine the velocity of a
        function which measure position. 
      </p>
      <p>
        Like growth rates, there are many version of this problem.
        For anything that changes in time, I can ask how fast it is
        changing. The velocity problem dealt with position over time,
        but actually any function of time leads to the same question.
        If heat depends on time, how fast is the heat increasing or
        decreasing? If happiness depends on time, how fast is
        happiness increasing or decreasing? This is all essentially
        the same motivating problem: finding the rate of change given
        a function that depends on time. 
      </p>
    </subsubsection>
    <subsubsection xml:id="subsubsection-motivating-distance">
      <title>Motivating Problem: Distance Travelled</title>
      <p>
        Now I will consider the opposite problem. Consider a function
        <m>v(t)</m> which tells me the velocity of an object at any
        point of time. How can I determine the distance the object has
        covered over a period of time? Again, in the special situation
        where the velocity is constant, algebra can solve this. 
      </p>
      <figure xml:id="figure-constant-velocity">
        <caption>Constant Velocity</caption>
        <image xml:id="figure14" width="60%">
          <asymptote>
            size(10cm);
  
            import graph;
  
            xaxis("$t$");
            yaxis("$y$");
  
            draw((0,4)--(6,4)--(6,0));
            
            label("$v(t) = c$",(3,4),N);
  
            dot("$t=0$",(0,0),NE);
            dot("$t=t_0$",(6,0),NW);
  
            label("Area$= ct_0$",(2,2),E);
          </asymptote>
        </image>
      </figure>
      <p>
        If velocity is constant, the I just multiply velocty by time.
        Velocity is units of distance per unit of time: multiplying by
        time gives the total distance. Travelling at 40 km/h for 3
        hours means you have travelled <m>40 \cdot 3 = 120</m>km.
        Algebra can do this. 
      </p>
      <p>
        Geometrically, in <xref ref="figure-constant-velocity"/>, the
        velociy is the height of the graph and the time is the witdh.
        The product of the two is height times width, which is just
        area. The velocity travelled is the area under the velocity
        graph. 
      </p>
      <p>
        If the velocity is non-constant, then I get a more complicated
        graph. 
      </p>
      <figure xml:id="figure-non-constant-velocity">
        <caption>Non-Constant Velocity</caption>
        <image xml:id="figure15" width="60%">
          <asymptote>
            size(10cm);
  
            import graph;
  
            xaxis("$x$");
            yaxis("$y$");
  
            draw((0,3){SE}..{E}(2,1.6){E}..{NE}(4,4){NE}..{SE}(6,3));
            draw((6,3)--(6,0));
  
            label("$v(t)$",(3,3),N);
  
            dot("$t=0$",(0,0),NE);
            dot("$t=t_0$",(6,0),NW);
            
            label("Area = Distance Travelled",(0.2,1),E);
          </asymptote>
        </image>
      </figure>
      <p>
        The distance travelled is still the area underneath this graph.
        Therefore, to solve the distance travelled problem, I need to
        find areas under curves. Liketangent lines, this is not a
        problem that algebra can easily tackle. This is a complicated
        area under a curving path: there is no easy formula for algebra
        to apply. 
      </p>
      <p>
        This is the third motivating problem. Geometrically, given a
        graph, can I calculate the area underneath the graph. In physics
        terms, this means starting with a velocity function and
        determining the total distance travelled. 
      </p>
      <p>
        Like the two previous problem, there are many versions of this
        problem. Velociy measure how fast your are travelling, so
        distance travelled is the total accomplish by travelling.
        Anytime I consider a function which directly describes a 
        rate of something being accomplish, then the area under that
        curve is the total amount of <sq>work</sq> accomplished by that
        function. If I have a function that measures the rate of water
        usage in a population, the area is the total amount of water
        consumed. If I have a funciton that measures the interest rate
        on a bank account, then the area is the total amount of interest
        gained. I could go on: any <sq>work accomplished</sq> probelm
        also fits this pattern. Any for any of these problems, if the
        situation is non-linear, I need new techique beyond algebra to
        solve it. 
      </p>
    </subsubsection>
    <subsubsection xml:id="subsubsection-motivating-optmization">
      <title>Motivating Problem: Optimization</title>
      <p>
        One final motivating problem. 
      </p>
    </subsubsection>
  </subsection>
</section>
